definition.value: Anatomical structure, each instance of which is a subdivision of some tissue demarcated by bonafide or fiat boundaries. Examples: stratum germinativum, lamina of cerebral cortex.
A component of the epithelium composed of a particular tissue.

Anatomical space which contains portions of one or more body substances and is bounded by the internal surface of one maximally connected anatomical structure or two or more adjacent anatomical structures.
Cardinal organ part, each instance of which is a fiat subdivision of some organ.
Subdivision of breast which consists of skin, connective tissue and smooth muscle bundle, modified sebaceous glands and papillary part of lactiferous duct.
Subdivision of the epidermis; a tissue component of the epithelium.
Individual hairs on the face taken together as a set.
Individual hairs taken together as a set.

Skin-associated structures that serve a particular function including sensation, contractility, lubrication and heat loss. In humans, some of the more common skin appendages are hairs (sensation, heat loss, filter for breathing, protection), arrector pilli (smooth muscles that pull hairs straight), sebaceous glands (secrete sebum onto hair follicle, which oils the hair), sweat glands (can secrete sweat with strong odour (apocrine) or with a faint odour (merocrine or eccrine)), and nails (protection).

Heterogeneous anatomical cluster, each instance of which has as its direct parts instances of two laminae of visceral peritoneum and regional parts of some gastrointestinal tract, vascular tree and neural tree.
Developmental organism which is a diploid nucleated cell that results from the union of the sperm and an ovum.
Region of anterior chest, each instance of which is an area of the anterior chest.
A gene that codes for any RNA or protein product other than a regulatory factor (i.e. regulatory protein).
The posterior border of the ovary.
The anterior border of the ovary.
The portions of the uterus to which the broad ligament is attached.
A grouping of anatomical folds.

The buttocks (singular: buttock) are two rounded portions of the anatomy, located on the posterior of the pelvic region of primates (including humans), and many other bipeds or quadrupeds, and comprise a layer of fat superimposed on the gluteus maximus and gluteus medius muscles.
A group of hymenal caruncles, considered together.

Structures of the vagina that are transverse ridges formed out of the supporting tissues and vaginal epithelium. Some conditions can cause the disappearance of vaginal rugae and are usually associated with childbirth and prolapse of pelvic structures.
Ridge at the lower anterior column of the vaginal rugae, parallel to the vagina.

The opening in the infundibulum of uterine tube into the abdominal cavity. In ovulation, the oocyte enters the Fallopian tube through this opening. It is surrounded by fimbriae, which help in the collection of the oocyte. Occlusion of this opening is referred to as distal tubal occlusion.
Either one of the pair of tubular extensions from the uterine body where the uterus and the uterine tubes meet; uterine horns are anterior Mullerian duct-derived structures.

The portion of the reproductive tract that connects the fallopian tubes to the uterus. The prominence of the uterine horns are variable across species and may be the location at which embryo implantation occurs in some species.
Organ segment which is regional part of cervix.
Supravaginal portion of cervix: the part of the cervix uteri that does not protrude into the vagina.
The growing corpus luteum; referring to as such due to its red coloration.
The serosa of the testis.
The subserosa of the testis.
Excretion in gaseous state processed in the stomach and small intestine.
Production or presence of gas in the gastrointestinal tract which may be expelled through the anus.

label.value: set of subdivisions of cardinal body part

definition.value: A group of individual subdivisions of a cardinal body part.
A grouping of components of an organ.
A grouping of regions of an organ.
Tags that are left behind following hymen rupture; they are pink and form a ring at the vaginal opening.
Anatomical set which has as its direct members, organs, organ parts and tissues of same or different types.

Organ component which consists of connective tissue that subdivides parenchyma into lobes, segments, lobules, acini, or cortex and medulla and the vascular and the neural networks intermixed with this connective tissue.

Anatomical structure, each instance of which has as its direct parts some instance of portions of two or more types of tissue and is continuous with some instance of one or more anatomical structures, likewise constituted by some portions of two or more tissues distinct from those of their complement.
Organ component which is a part of a wall of an organ or a membranous layer of an organ.
Organ component layer arranged in sheets or lamellae.
A peptide that is biogenic in nature.
Small proteins that function as hormonal signals, synthesized and secreted by one tissue or organ with physiological effects on other tissues or organs.
A neuropeptide which acts on the pituitary gland in order to stimulate the release of luteinizing hormone (LH).

Hormones that stimulate gonadal functions such as gametogenesis and sex steroid hormone production in the ovary and the testis. Major gonadotropins are glycoproteins produced primarily by the adenohypophysis (gonadotropins, pituitary) and the placenta (chorionic gonadotropin). In some species, pituitary prolactin and placental lactogen exert some luteotropic activities.
An area or region of a DNA molecule.

An exon is a nucleic acid sequence that is represented in the mature form of an RNA molecule either after portions of a precursor RNA (introns) have been removed by cis-splicing or when two or more precursor RNA molecules have been ligated by trans-splicing.
The sequences of a gene that are present in the final, mature, spliced messenger RNA molecule from that gene.
Non-coding, intervening sequences of DNA that are transcribed, but are removed from within the primary gene transcript and rapidly degraded during maturation of messenger RNA.
A folded part or structure which is anatomical in nature (such as skin or muscle which is folded).
Organ component layer, each instance of which is lining the internal side of some organ.
The subserosa of an organ.
Cardinal organ part. each instance of which is a fiat subdivision of some organ component.
